icle><div class=3D"page-wrapper PostDetail_wrapper__ea9fY"><div class=3D"Po=
stDetail_post-heading__LeDFA"><div class=3D"PostDetail_post-detail-types-su=
bjects__rYglE"><span class=3D"PostDetail_post-subject__Kpz7U PostDetail_dis=
abled__zFGBd PostDetail_chip__oT3gx detail-s">Alignment</span></div><h1 cla=
ss=3D"h2">Constitutional Classifiers: Defending against universal jailbreak=
s</h1><div class=3D"PostDetail_post-timestamp__TBJ0Z text-label">Feb 3, 202=
5</div></div><div class=3D"text-b2 PostDetail_post-detail__6Ldh_"><article>=
<div class=3D""><div class=3D"Body_body__XEXq7"><p class=3D"Body_reading-co=
lumn__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text"><em>A <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2=
501.18837">new paper</a> from the Anthropic Safeguards Research Team descri=
bes a method that defends AI models against universal jailbreaks. A prototy=
pe version of the method was robust to thousands of hours of human red team=
ing for universal jailbreaks, albeit with high overrefusal rates and comput=
e overhead. An updated version achieved similar robustness on synthetic eva=
luations, and did so with a 0.38% increase in refusal rates and moderate ad=
ditional compute costs.</em></p><div class=3D"Body_media-column__xPzhg"><di=
v class=3D"VideoEmbed_e-videoEmbed__1eFwQ" style=3D"width: 100%; height: au=
to;"><div style=3D"width: 100%; height: 100%;"><iframe frameborder=3D"0" al=
lowfullscreen=3D"" allow=3D"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encry=
pted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" referrerpolicy=3D"str=
ict-origin-when-cross-origin" title=3D"Defending against AI jailbreaks" wid=
th=3D"100%" height=3D"100%" src=3D"cid:frame-648932F4C8A64F4AEE0A352F5FB01F=
A1@mhtml.blink" id=3D"widget2"></iframe></div></div></div><p class=3D"Body_=
reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">Large language models have ext=
ensive safety training to prevent harmful outputs. For example, we train Cl=
aude to refuse to respond to user queries involving the production of biolo=
gical or chemical weapons.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragr=
aph-m post-text">Nevertheless, models are still vulnerable to <em>jailbreak=
s</em>: inputs designed to bypass their safety guardrails and force them to=
 produce harmful responses. Some jailbreaks flood the model with <a href=3D=
"https://www.anthropic.com/research/many-shot-jailbreaking">very long promp=
ts</a>; others modify the <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2412.03556">styl=
e of the input</a>, such as uSiNg uNuSuAl cApItALiZaTiOn. Historically, jai=
lbreaks have proved difficult to detect and block: these kinds of attacks w=
ere <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/1312.6199">described over 10 years ago=
</a>, yet to our knowledge there are still no fully robust deep-learning mo=
dels in production.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m p=
ost-text">We=E2=80=99re developing better jailbreak defenses so that we can=
 safely deploy increasingly capable models in the future. Under our <a href=
=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/news/announcing-our-updated-responsible-scali=
ng-policy">Responsible Scaling Policy</a>, we may deploy such models as lon=
g as we=E2=80=99re able to mitigate risks to acceptable levels through appr=
opriate safeguards=E2=80=94but jailbreaking lets users bypass these safegua=
rds. In particular, we=E2=80=99re hopeful that a system defended by Constit=
utional Classifiers could allow us to mitigate jailbreaking risks for model=
s which have passed the CBRN capability threshold outlined in our Responsib=
le Scaling Policy<sup class=3D"detail-s agate">1</sup>.</p><p class=3D"Body=
_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">In <a href=3D"https://arxiv.o=
rg/abs/2501.18837"><strong>our new paper</strong></a>, we describe a system=
 based on <em>Constitutional Classifiers</em> that guards models against ja=
ilbreaks. These Constitutional Classifiers are input and output classifiers=
 trained on synthetically generated data that filter the overwhelming major=
ity of jailbreaks with minimal over-refusals and without incurring a large =
compute overhead.</p><h2 class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM display-sans-s=
 post-section" id=3D"results-from-human-red-teaming">Results from human red=
 teaming</h2><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">=
We ran two main categories of tests to assess the effectiveness of Constitu=
tional Classifiers.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m p=
ost-text">First, we developed a prototype version of the system to identify=
 and block specific scientific knowledge related to chemical, biological, r=
adiological, and nuclear harms. We then invited independent jailbreakers to=
 a <a href=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/news/model-safety-bug-bounty">bug-b=
ounty program</a> in which they were challenged to =E2=80=9Cred team=E2=80=
=9D the system (i.e., to attempt to break it under experimental conditions =
to test its robustness).</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragrap=
h-m post-text">Specifically, they were given a list of ten =E2=80=9Cforbidd=
en=E2=80=9D queries, and their task was to use whichever jailbreaking techn=
iques they wanted in order to get one of our current models (in this case, =
Claude 3.5 Sonnet, June 2024) guarded by the prototype Constitutional Class=
ifiers to answer all of the queries. We only considered it a successful =E2=
=80=9Cuniversal=E2=80=9D jailbreak if the model provided a detailed answer =
to <em>all</em> of the queries.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM p=
aragraph-m post-text">183 active<sup class=3D"detail-s agate">2</sup> parti=
cipants spent an estimated &gt;3,000 hours over a two-month experimental pe=
riod attempting to jailbreak the model. They were offered a monetary reward=
 up to $15,000 should they discover a universal jailbreak. Despite the larg=
e amount of effort, none of the participants were able to coerce the model =
to answer all ten forbidden queries with a single jailbreak=E2=80=94that is=
, no universal jailbreak was discovered.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column=
__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">Despite its robustness to jailbreaks, this p=
rototype system had some problems: it refused too many harmless queries and=
 cost a lot of computational resources to run. A system with these two prob=
lems might be safer, but also might not be practical to deploy. Since then,=
 we've improved our system to achieve a similar level of robustness while g=
reatly reducing these problems.</p><h2 class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM =
display-sans-s post-section" id=3D"results-from-automated-evaluations">Resu=
lts from automated evaluations</h2><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM p=
aragraph-m post-text">We ran a set of automated evaluations where we synthe=
tically generated 10,000 jailbreaking prompts including many of the most-ef=
fective attacks on current LLMs, as well as attacks designed to circumvent =
classifier safeguards. We tried these prompts on a version of Claude 3.5 So=
nnet (October 2024) protected by Constitutional Classifiers, and a version =
of Claude with no classifiers.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM pa=
ragraph-m post-text">Under baseline conditions, with no defensive classifie=
rs, the jailbreak success rate was 86%=E2=80=94that is, Claude itself block=
ed only 14% of these advanced jailbreak attempts. Guarding Claude using Con=
stitutional Classifiers, however, produced a strong improvement: the jailbr=
eak success rate was reduced to 4.4%, meaning that over 95% of jailbreak at=
tempts were refused.</p><div class=3D"Body_media-column__xPzhg"><figure cla=
ss=3D"ImageWithCaption_e-imageWithCaption__8C2mY ImageWithCaption_inline-im=
age__B15e_"><img alt=3D"A graph showing the results for vulnerability to ja=
ilbreaks, overrefusals, and compute overhead for the Constitutional Classif=
iers system versus the base model" loading=3D"lazy" width=3D"1650" height=
=3D"1077" decoding=3D"async" data-nimg=3D"1" style=3D"color:transparent" sr=
c=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/_next/image?url=3Dhttps%3A%2F%2Fwww-cdn.anth=
ropic.com%2Fimages%2F4zrzovbb%2Fwebsite%2Fcd6520ed645ade7f12ab336cd02ef5954=
211dfa8-1650x1077.png&amp;w=3D3840&amp;q=3D75"><figcaption class=3D"text-ca=
ption"><em>Results from automated evaluations. For all plots, lower is bett=
er. (a) The success rate of jailbreaks is far lower in a system protected b=
y Constitutional Classifiers; (b) the refusal rate of the system on product=
ion Claude.ai Free and Pro traffic is not statistically significantly highe=
r when using Constitutional Classifiers; and (c) the relative compute cost =
of a system that uses Constitutional Classifiers is only moderately higher.=
 Error bars represent 95% confidence intervals computed using binomial prop=
ortion standard errors under asymptotic normality assumptions.</em></figcap=
tion></figure></div><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post=
-text">At the same time, our Constitutional Classifiers did not substantial=
ly increase the over-refusal rate on harmless user queries: with the classi=
fiers, Claude had a slightly increased refusal rate (by 0.38%), but this wa=
s not statistically significant in a random sample of 5,000 conversations. =
Finally, the compute cost was moderately higher (by 23.7%) than that of the=
 unguarded model. We=E2=80=99re working on reducing refusals and compute co=
st even further as we refine the technique.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-col=
umn__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">Overall, our automated analyses found tha=
t this updated version of the Constitutional Classifiers system dramaticall=
y improved the robustness of the AI model against jailbreaking=E2=80=94and =
did so with only minimal additional cost.</p><h2 class=3D"Body_reading-colu=
mn__t7kGM display-sans-s post-section" id=3D"how-it-works">How it works</h2=
><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">Constitution=
al Classifiers is based on a similar process to <a href=3D"https://arxiv.or=
g/abs/2212.08073">Constitutional AI</a>, another technique we have <a href=
=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/research/claude-character">used to align Clau=
de</a>. Both techniques use a constitution: a list of principles to which t=
he model should adhere. In the case of Constitutional Classifiers, the prin=
ciples define the classes of content that are allowed and disallowed (for e=
xample, recipes for mustard are allowed, but recipes for mustard gas are no=
t).</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">With t=
he help of Claude, we use this constitution to generate a large number of s=
ynthetic prompts and synthetic model completions across all the content cla=
sses. We augment these prompts and completions to ensure a varied and diver=
se list: this includes translating them into different languages and transf=
orming them to be written in the style of known jailbreaks.</p><div class=
=3D"Body_media-column__xPzhg"><figure class=3D"ImageWithCaption_e-imageWith=
Caption__8C2mY ImageWithCaption_inline-image__B15e_"><img alt=3D"A schemati=
c diagram of the how the Constitutional Classifiers system works, from the =
creation of the constitution through to generating a test set to using the =
system to guard an LLM" loading=3D"lazy" width=3D"1650" height=3D"1077" dec=
oding=3D"async" data-nimg=3D"1" style=3D"color:transparent" src=3D"https://=
www.anthropic.com/_next/image?url=3Dhttps%3A%2F%2Fwww-cdn.anthropic.com%2Fi=
mages%2F4zrzovbb%2Fwebsite%2F2e997f9fca176fd82966ea5e9bf000873337cfd1-1650x=
1077.jpg&amp;w=3D3840&amp;q=3D75"><figcaption class=3D"text-caption"><em>Tr=
aining and implementing Constitutional Classifiers. (a) A constitution is p=
roduced specifying harmless and harmful categories; (b) the constitution is=
 used as the basis for the production of many synthetic prompts and complet=
ions, which are further augmented (with variations on style and language) a=
nd turned into a training set; (c) classifiers trained on this training set=
 are used as model safeguards to detect and block harmful content.</em></fi=
gcaption></figure></div><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m =
post-text">We then use these synthetic data to train our input and output c=
lassifiers to flag (and block) potentially harmful content according to the=
 given constitution. To help minimize over-refusals (i.e., harmless content=
 incorrectly flagged as harmful), we also train the classifiers on a fixed =
set of benign queries generated by a contractor.</p><h2 class=3D"Body_readi=
ng-column__t7kGM display-sans-s post-section" id=3D"limitations">Limitation=
s</h2><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">Constit=
utional Classifiers may not prevent every universal jailbreak, though we be=
lieve that even the small proportion of jailbreaks that make it past our cl=
assifiers require far more effort to discover when the safeguards are in us=
e. It=E2=80=99s also possible that new jailbreaking techniques might be dev=
eloped in the future that are effective against the system; we therefore re=
commend using <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2411.07494">complementary</a=
> <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2411.17693">defenses</a>. Nevertheless, =
the constitution used to train the classifiers can rapidly be adapted to co=
ver novel attacks as they=E2=80=99re discovered.</p><p class=3D"Body_readin=
g-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">The <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs=
/2501.18837">full paper</a> contains all the details about the Constitution=
al Classifiers method, and about the classifiers themselves.</p><h2 class=
=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM display-sans-s post-section" id=3D"constitut=
ional-classifiers-live-demo">Constitutional Classifiers live demo</h2><p cl=
ass=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">Want to try red te=
aming Claude yourself? We invite you to try out a <a href=3D"https://claude=
.ai/constitutional-classifiers">demo of our Constitutional-Classifiers-guar=
ded system</a> and attempt to jailbreak a version of Claude 3.5 Sonnet that=
 is guarded using our new technique.<strong> [Edit 10 February 2025: The de=
mo is now complete. See below for details].</strong></p><p class=3D"Body_re=
ading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">Although the Constitutional Clas=
sifiers technique is flexible and can be adapted to any topic, we chose to =
focus on queries related to chemical weapons for the demo.</p><p class=3D"B=
ody_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">Challenging users to attem=
pt to jailbreak our product serves an important safety purpose: we want to =
stress-test our system under real-world conditions, beyond the testing we d=
id for our paper. This allows us to gather additional data and improve the =
robustness of the method prior to deploying this method on our production s=
ystems in the future.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m=
 post-text">The <a href=3D"https://claude.ai/constitutional-classifiers"><s=
trong>demo</strong></a> will be live from <strong>Feb 3, 2025</strong> to <=
strong>Feb 10, 2025</strong>. It includes a feedback form where you can con=
tact us to report any successful jailbreaks as well as information on our <=
a href=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/responsible-disclosure-policy">Responsi=
ble Disclosure Policy</a>, which we ask that participants follow. We=E2=80=
=99ll announce any successes and the general results of the demo in an upda=
te to this post.</p><h2 class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM display-sans-s =
post-section" id=3D"13-february-2025-update-live-demo-results">13 February =
2025 update: Live demo results</h2><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM p=
aragraph-m post-text">The goal of our demo was to test our system=E2=80=99s=
 robustness to <em>universal</em> jailbreaks=E2=80=94prompting strategies t=
hat could elicit detailed, harmful information from the system across all e=
ight questions that we provided. By the end of the demo, one jailbreaker wa=
s able to get detailed answers from the system for all eight questions usin=
g a universal jailbreak.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragrap=
h-m post-text">Our demo generated significant engagement from the AI securi=
ty community, with 339 jailbreakers<sup class=3D"detail-s agate">3</sup> at=
tempting to jailbreak our system across more than 300,000 chat interactions=
, representing approximately 3,700 collective hours of red-teaming effort.<=
/p><h3 class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM display-sans-xs post-subsection"=
 id=3D"key-findings">Key findings</h3><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kG=
M paragraph-m post-text">The system resisted jailbreaking attempts for five=
 of the planned seven days. Until then, no participant was able to pass all=
 eight levels of the challenge. On the sixth and seventh day, <strong>four =
participants successfully cleared all levels. </strong>Of these four, <stro=
ng>one discovered what we determined to be a universal jailbreak</strong>. =
Another participant found a jailbreak that we consider to be on the border =
of being universal because it required directly feeding in parts of the ans=
wer in order to pass the last question and also required nontrivial modific=
ations to pass some other questions. The remaining two participants obtaine=
d detailed answers to all 8 questions, but we determined that their jailbre=
aks did not meet the criteria for being considered <em>universal </em>outli=
ned in <a href=3D"https://hackerone.com/constitutional-classifiers?type=3Dt=
eam">our contest guidelines</a>.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM =
paragraph-m post-text">The most successful jailbreaking strategies included=
:</p><ul class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text"><li>Usi=
ng various ciphers and encodings to circumvent the output classifier.</li><=
li>Employing role-play scenarios, often through system prompts.</li><li>Sub=
stituting harmful keywords with innocuous alternatives (e.g., replacing =E2=
=80=9CSoman=E2=80=9D [a dangerous chemical] with =E2=80=9Cwater=E2=80=9D).<=
/li><li>Implementing prompt-injection attacks.</li></ul><div class=3D"Body_=
media-column__xPzhg"><figure class=3D"ImageWithCaption_e-imageWithCaption__=
8C2mY ImageWithCaption_full-width-image__Ae0bz ImageWithCaption_narrow__qFY=
Cv"><img loading=3D"lazy" width=3D"1800" height=3D"1800" decoding=3D"async"=
 data-nimg=3D"1" style=3D"color:transparent" src=3D"https://www.anthropic.c=
om/_next/image?url=3Dhttps%3A%2F%2Fwww-cdn.anthropic.com%2Fimages%2F4zrzovb=
b%2Fwebsite%2F0caa7bd830986ef74a79a277655bee7e313cbe94-1800x1800.png&amp;w=
=3D3840&amp;q=3D75"><figcaption class=3D"text-caption">Bar graph showing th=
e number of users that passed each level of the challenge. 339 users passed=
 question 1, and only 4 users passed question 8.</figcaption></figure></div=
><h3 class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM display-sans-xs post-subsection" i=
d=3D"auto-grader-analysis">Auto-grader analysis</h3><p class=3D"Body_readin=
g-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">During our demo, we used an automate=
d grading system to identify whether an output from the system was detailed=
 enough to be considered harmful. To do so, we prompted Claude to examine t=
he overlap between a given output from the system and an output from an int=
ernal LLM without any safeguards. Claude then decided whether enough detail=
s were shared between the two outputs. Our automated grader system, while e=
ffective, had some areas for improvement:</p><ul class=3D"Body_reading-colu=
mn__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text"><li>After reviewing the grading system=E2=
=80=99s records, we found that the grader was refusing to grade approximate=
ly 1% of submissions across all questions. Question 4 showed a higher refus=
al rate of 10%.</li><li>Upon review, approximately 1% of the Question 4 ref=
usals would have passed if the grader had been rerun with additional output=
-deobfuscation steps and used a helpful-only model.</li><li>In total, 0.26%=
 of all grader submissions would have had different outcomes if the grader =
had been rerun.</li></ul><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m=
 post-text">In most of these cases, users simply reran the grader, which he=
lped overcome this challenge. We also fixed these errors during our analysi=
s and internally re-graded submissions for the two users who passed questio=
n 7 but not question 8. Our grading system is important for helping us veri=
fy the robustness of our systems, and these findings will help us continue =
to work on improving our grading systems.</p><h3 class=3D"Body_reading-colu=
mn__t7kGM display-sans-xs post-subsection" id=3D"comparison-to-real-world-t=
hreats">Comparison to real-world threats</h3><p class=3D"Body_reading-colum=
n__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">Our demo had two important differences from=
 real-world scenarios. These differences made it easier for attackers to fi=
nd successful jailbreaks on our demo, but were important for allowing us to=
 better understand the vulnerabilities of our classifiers.</p><p class=3D"B=
ody_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">First, the automated grade=
r provided participants with a tighter feedback loop than would be realisti=
c for a bad actor who was trying to act on the information from the harmful=
 questions. In practice, a bad actor would only be able to test the quality=
 of a given model response by actually trying to follow the response=E2=80=
=99s instructions=E2=80=94a task that=E2=80=99s significantly more difficul=
t and time-intensive than using the grader that we provided.</p><p class=3D=
"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">Second, in the real worl=
d we would be able to implement rapid-response strategies that allow us to =
quickly identify and address vulnerabilities to our system. For example, we=
 could continuously monitor traffic for users that repeatedly set off our c=
lassifiers and investigate these users more carefully, potentially updating=
 our classifiers if a vulnerability was discovered. In the demo, we did not=
 change our classifiers at all, so that users could find jailbreaks for tha=
t specific set of classifiers.</p><h3 class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM d=
isplay-sans-xs post-subsection" id=3D"prizes">Prizes</h3><p class=3D"Body_r=
eading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">On February 5, we <a href=3D"ht=
tps://x.com/AnthropicAI/status/1887227067156386027">announced</a> a cash pr=
ize of $10K to the first person to pass all eight levels, and $20K to the f=
irst person to pass all eight levels with a universal jailbreak. Both of th=
ese prizes were won, each by a separate jailbreaker. To recognize the effor=
t needed to jailbreak our system, we=E2=80=99ve decided to pay additional p=
rizes to the other two users who passed all 8 levels of the challenge but d=
id not qualify for the original prizes. In total, we=E2=80=99ll pay out $55=
K to the four users who succeeded at beating all 8 levels of our demo.</p><=
h3 class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM display-sans-xs post-subsection" id=
=3D"winners">Winners</h3><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m=
 post-text">We=E2=80=99d like to thank the following jailbreakers for their=
 effort on jailbreaking our system:</p><ul class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7=
kGM paragraph-m post-text"><li><strong>Altynbek Ismailov and Salia Asanova<=
/strong>: the first participant (team) to pass all eight levels of the chal=
lenge using what we considered to be a universal jailbreak.</li><li><strong=
>Valen Tagliabue</strong>: the first participant to pass all eight levels o=
f the challenge.</li><li><strong>Hunter Senft-Grupp</strong>: passed all ei=
ght levels of the challenge using what we considered to be a borderline-uni=
versal jailbreak.</li><li><strong>Andres Aldana</strong>: passed all eight =
levels of the challenge.</li></ul><h3 class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM d=
isplay-sans-xs post-subsection" id=3D"looking-ahead">Looking Ahead</h3><p c=
lass=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">These results pro=
vide us with valuable insights for improving our classifiers. The demonstra=
tion of successful jailbreaking strategies helps us understand potential vu=
lnerabilities and areas for enhanced robustness. We=E2=80=99ll continue to =
analyze the results, and will incorporate what we find into future iteratio=
ns of the system. We=E2=80=99ll also be furthering our efforts to reduce ou=
r system=E2=80=99s over-refusal rates and compute overhead costs while main=
taining an acceptable level of robustness to jailbreaks.</p><p class=3D"Bod=
y_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">Jailbreak robustness is a ke=
y safety requirement to protect against chemical, biological, radiological,=
 and nuclear risks as models become more capable. Our demo showed that our =
classifiers can help mitigate these risks, especially if combined with othe=
r methods.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text"=
>We extend our gratitude to all participants who contributed their time and=
 expertise to this demonstration. Their efforts have provided invaluable da=
ta for improving AI safety.</p><h2 class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM disp=
lay-sans-s post-section" id=3D"change-log">Change log</h2><p class=3D"Body_=
reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">*Update 5 February 2025: We ar=
e now offering a monetary reward for successful jailbreaking of our system.=
 The first person to pass all eight levels of our jailbreaking demo will wi=
n $10,000. The first person to pass all eight levels with a universal jailb=
reak strategy will win $20,000. Full details of the reward and the associat=
ed conditions can be found at <a href=3D"https://hackerone.com/constitution=
al-classifiers">HackerOne</a>.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM pa=
ragraph-m post-text">**Update 10 February 2025: The live jailbreaking demo =
is now complete. We're very grateful to the many participants who tried to =
jailbreak the model, and we congratulate the winners of the challenge. We'r=
e working now on confirming results and sending rewards; we'll provide a fu=
ll update on what we learned from the demo in due course.</p><p class=3D"Bo=
dy_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">***Update 13 February 2025:=
 Added the "Live demo results" section.</p><p class=3D"Body_reading-column_=
_t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">****Update 18 February 2025: Added the names =
of the winning jailbreakers.</p><h2 class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM dis=
play-sans-s post-section" id=3D"acknowledgements">Acknowledgements</h2><p c=
lass=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">We=E2=80=99d like=
 to thank <a href=3D"https://www.hackerone.com/">HackerOne</a> for supporti=
ng our bug-bounty program for red teaming our prototype system. We are also=
 grateful to <a href=3D"https://www.haizelabs.com/">Haize Labs</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://www.grayswan.ai/">Gray Swan</a>, and the <a href=3D"https://www=
.aisi.gov.uk/">UK AI Safety Institute</a> for red teaming other prototype v=
ersions of our system.</p><h2 class=3D"Body_reading-column__t7kGM display-s=
ans-s post-section" id=3D"join-our-team">Join our team</h2><p class=3D"Body=
_reading-column__t7kGM paragraph-m post-text">If you=E2=80=99re interested =
in working on problems such as jailbreak robustness or on other questions r=
elated to model safeguards, we=E2=80=99re currently recruiting for <a href=
=3D"https://boards.greenhouse.io/anthropic/jobs/4459012008">Research Engine=
ers / Scientists</a>, and we=E2=80=99d love to see your application.</p></d=
iv></div></article><div class=3D"PostDetail_post-footnotes__y7xQR footnotes=
